        headingId: "selecting-b2b-software-key-evaluation-criteria",
        content: `<p>With hundreds of B2B software options available, industrial companies need a <strong>structured evaluation framework</strong> to make informed decisions:</p>
<h3>Industry Fit</h3>
<p>Prioritize software vendors with <strong>proven experience in industrial distribution and manufacturing</strong>. Generic solutions often require extensive customization to handle industry-specific requirements like serial number tracking, lot management, hazardous materials compliance, and equipment-based ordering. Ask vendors for references from companies similar to yours in size and industry.</p>
<h3>Integration Architecture</h3>
<p>Evaluate how the software integrates with your <strong>existing technology stack</strong>. Look for pre-built connectors to your ERP, native API support, and middleware compatibility. The total cost of integration often exceeds the software license cost, so understanding integration requirements upfront is essential for accurate budgeting.</p>
<h3>Scalability and Performance</h3>
<p>Ensure the software can handle your <strong>current and projected data volumes</strong>. For eCommerce platforms, this means supporting large product catalogs (100K+ SKUs), high concurrent user counts during peak periods, and fast page load times even with complex pricing calculations. Ask vendors about their largest customers and performance benchmarks.</p>
<h3>Total Cost of Ownership</h3>
<p>Calculate the <strong>full cost over 3-5 years</strong>, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>License or subscription fees</li>
<li>Implementation and configuration costs</li>
<li>Integration development</li>
<li>Training and change management</li>
<li>Ongoing maintenance, support, and upgrades</li>
</ul>
<p>Cloud-native SaaS solutions typically offer <strong>lower TCO and faster time-to-value</strong> compared to on-premise or heavily customized platforms.</p>`
